6-story Kumbum, was the greatest Tibetan Buddhist Kumbum of its time (now destroyed). Tibetan name listed in Xian Wenwuzhi in pinyin as: "Gongbeng Tongzhui Qiongba Ta". Located 450 m from Tropu monastery.
founding date not clear, but cult at site dates to figures of the phyi dar period, so use 1100 as general date 'till better data available.
Had 85 monks. Name not clear, Xian Wenwuzhi lists "Sai jui ba", and TAR 9-sheet Tibetan map shows a village of Badur at this site, so use "Badur" for now.

Had 25 monks. A Songstan Gampo temple according to Xian Wenwuzhi. Only Chinese name of "Baima Qulin" listed. Map as 'Padma' for Imperial period, then when becomes Nyingma c. 1850 list name as 'Padma Choling'.

1.9 m Chorten of Imperial period style according to Xian Wenwuzhi. Located along a Tibet-India trade route (not where main highway of today runs). Name not clear, but name of village can be used for now as name 'till better data available.

Xian Wenwuzhi cannot confirm date, but clearly was a Kadampa site it states. So date of 1050 approximate 'till better data available. Possibly the mngon dga' chos sde dgon (Kagyu w/53 monks) of TAR 1950s gonpa list (Shelkar dzong part), because Xian Wen

Had 80 monks. According to Xian Wenwuzhi volume, a site named "Qu Guo Lun Bao" (in Chinese) was built, destroyed in 1970s, but in 1982 a Guru Rinpoche shrine was rebuilt on site, thus this is probably the Ogyan temple of Chophel's contemporary survey gu

Founding date estimated based on site noted as being held by the 'continuators' of tshar chen blo gsal rgya mtsho (1502-1567). Khentse notes tomb of tshar chen here. Gene says this site had its own tradition.
Founding date from Ferrari, Bodong conversion implied as Bo dong phyogs las rnam rgyal (1306-1386) resided here at the end of his life.
